#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:209
#, no-c-format
msgid "Settings done in a <filename>bashrc</filename> file require that you open a new shell window. Settings done in a <filename>profile</filename> file require that you log in into the system. You can, of course, also give the commands in the current shell."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:222
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing Eclipse IDE"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:229
#, no-c-format
msgid "Download the Eclipse IDE for Java EE Developers from <link xlink:href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/\"> http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/</link>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid "Decompress the Eclipse IDE package to a suitable directory. You are free to select any directory and to use any ZIP decompressor, but in this example we decompress the ZIP file by just double-clicking it and selecting \"Extract all files\" task from Windows compressed folder task. In our installation example, we use <filename>C:\\dev</filename> as the target directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:249
#, no-c-format
msgid "Eclipse is now installed in <filename>C:\\dev\\eclipse</filename> and can be started from there (by double clicking eclipse.exe)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:256
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linux / OS X / UNIX"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:258
#, no-c-format
msgid "We recommend that you install Eclipse manually in Linux and other UNIX variants as follows."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:265
#, no-c-format
msgid "Download Eclipse IDE for Java EE Developers from <link xlink:href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/\"> http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/</link>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:272
#, no-c-format
msgid "Decompress the Eclipse package into a suitable base directory. It is important to make sure that there is no old Eclipse installation in the target directory. Installing a new version on top of an old one probably renders Eclipse unusable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:280
#, no-c-format
msgid "Eclipse should normally be installed as a regular user, as this makes installation of plugins easier. Eclipse also stores some user settings in the installation directory. To install the package, enter: <screen><prompt>$</prompt> <command>tar</command> zxf <replaceable>(path-to-installation-package)/eclipse-jee-ganymede-SR2-linux-gtk.tar.gz</replaceable></screen> This will extract the package to a subdirectory with the name <filename>eclipse</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:294
#, no-c-format
msgid "You may wish to add the Eclipse installation directory and the <filename>bin</filename> subdirectory in the installation directory of Java SDK to your system or user PATH."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:302
#, no-c-format
msgid "An alternative to the above procedure would be to use an Eclipse version available through the package management system of your operating system. It is, however, <emphasis>not recommended</emphasis>, because you will need write access to the Eclipse installation directory to install Eclipse plugins, and you may face incompatibility issues with Eclipse plugins installed by the package management of the operating system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:316
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing Apache Tomcat"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:318
#, no-c-format
msgid "Apache Tomcat is a lightweight Java web server suitable for both development and production. There are many ways to install it, but here we simply decompress the installation package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:324
#, no-c-format
msgid "<emphasis>Apache Tomcat should be installed with user permissions.</emphasis> During development, you will be running Eclipse or some other IDE with user permissions, but deploying web applications to a Tomcat server that is installed system-wide requires administrator or root permissions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid "Download the installation package:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:337
#, no-c-format
msgid "Apache Tomcat 7.0 (Core Binary Distribution) from <uri>http://tomcat.apache.org/</uri>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:344
#, no-c-format
msgid "Decompress Apache Tomcat package to a suitable target directory, such as <filename>C:\\dev</filename> (Windows) or <filename>/opt</filename> (Linux or Mac OS X). The Apache Tomcat home directory will be <filename>C:\\dev\\apache-tomcat-7.0.x</filename> or <filename>/opt/apache-tomcat-7.0.x</filename>, respectively."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:359
#, no-c-format
msgid "Firefox and Firebug"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:361
#, no-c-format
msgid "Vaadin supports many web browsers and you can use any of them for development. If you plan to create a custom theme, customized layouts, or create new components, we recommend that you use either Firefox together with Firebug or Google Chrome, which has built-in developer tools similar to Firebug."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Firebug with Vaadin"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid "After installing Firefox, use it to open <link xlink:href=\"http://www.getfirebug.com/\"> http://www.getfirebug.com/</link>. Follow the instructions on the site to install the latest stable version of Firebug available for the browser. You may need to allow Firefox to install the plugin by clicking the yellow warning bar at the top of the browser window."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:381
#, no-c-format
msgid "After Firebug is installed, it can be enabled at any time from the Firefox toolbar. <xref linkend=\"figure.firebug.calc\"/> shows Firebug in action."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:388
#, no-c-format
msgid "Firebug Debugger for Firefox"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:399
#, no-c-format
msgid "The most important feature in Firebug is inspecting HTML elements. Right-click on an element and select <guilabel>Inspect Element with Firebug</guilabel> to inspect it. In addition to HTML tree, it also shows the CSS rules matching the element, which you can use for building themes. You can even edit the CSS styles live, to experiment with styling."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:412
#, no-c-format
msgid "Overview of Vaadin Libraries"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:414
#, no-c-format
msgid "Vaadin comes as a set of library JARs, of which some are optional or alternative ones, depending on whether you are developing server-side or client-side applications, whether you use add-on components, or use CSS or Sass themes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:423
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-server-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid "The main library for developing server-side Vaadin applications, as described in <xref linkend=\"application\"/>. It requires the <filename>vaadin-shared</filename> and the <filename>vaadin-themes</filename> libraries. You can use the prebuilt <filename>vaadin-client-compiled</filename> for server-side development, unless you need add-on components or custom widgets."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:437
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-shared-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:439
#, no-c-format
msgid "A shared library for server-side and client-side development. It is always needed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:446
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-client-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:448
#, no-c-format
msgid "The client-side Vaadin framework, including the basic GWT API and Vaadin-specific widgets and other additions. It is required when using the <filename>vaadin-client-compiler</filename> to compile client-side modules. It is not needed if you just use the server-side framework with the precompiled Client-Side Engine. You should not deploy it with a web application."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:459
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-client-compiler-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:461
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Vaadin Client Compiler is a Java-to-JavaScript compiler that allows building client-side modules, such as the Client-Side Engine (widget set) required for server-side applications. The compiler is needed, for example, for compiling add-on components to the application widget set, as described in <xref linkend=\"addons\"/>. For detailed information regarding the compiler, see <xref linkend=\"clientside.compiling\"/>. Note that you should not deploy this library with a web application."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:476
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-client-compiled-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:478
#, no-c-format
msgid "A precompiled Vaadin Client-Side Engine (widget set) that includes all the basic built-in widgets in Vaadin. This library is not needed if you compile the application widget set with the Vaadin Client Compiler."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:487
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-themes-&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid "Vaadin built-in themes both as SCSS source files and precompiled CSS files. The library is required both for basic use with CSS themes and for compiling custom Sass themes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:497
#, no-c-format
msgid "vaadin-theme-compiler&version.vaadin;.jar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:499
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Vaadin Theme Compiler compiles SASS themes to CSS, as described in <xref linkend=\"themes.sass\"/>. It requires the <filename>vaadin-themes-&version.vaadin;.jar</filename> library, which contains the SCSS sources for the built-in themes. The library needs to be included in deployment in development mode to allow on-the-fly compilation of themes, but it is not needed in production deployment, when the themes are compiled before deployment."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid "Some of the libraries depend on each other as well as on the dependency libraries provided in the <filename>lib</filename> folder of the installation package, especially the <filename>lib/vaadin-shared-deps.jar</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:519
#, no-c-format
msgid "The different ways to install the libraries are described in the subsequent sections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:523
#, no-c-format
msgid "Note that the <filename>vaadin-client-compiler</filename> and <filename>vaadin-client</filename> JARs should not be deployed with the web application by including them in <filename>WEB-INF/lib</filename>. Some other libraries, such as <filename>vaadin-theme-compiler</filename>, are not needed in production deployment."
msgstr ""

