#. Tag: title
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1923
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Vaadin with Scala"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1925
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can use Vaadin with any JVM compatible language, such as Scala or Groovy. There are, however, some caveats related to libraries and project set-up. In the following, we give instructions for creating a Scala UI in Eclipse, with the Scala IDE for Eclipse and the Vaadin Plugin for Eclipse."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1934
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the <link xlink:href=\"http://scala-ide.org/\">Scala IDE for Eclipse</link>, either from an Eclipse update site or as a bundled Eclipse distribution."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1942
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open an existing Vaadin Java project or create a new one as outlined in <xref linkend=\"getting-started.first-project\"/>. You can delete the UI class created by the wizard."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1950
#, no-c-format
msgid "Switch to the Scala perspective by clicking the perspective in the upper-right corner of the Eclipse window."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1957
#, no-c-format
msgid "Right-click on the project folder in <guilabel>Project Explorer</guilabel> and select <menuchoice><guimenu>Configure</guimenu><guimenuitem>Add Scala Nature</guimenuitem></menuchoice>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1965
#, no-c-format
msgid "The web application needs <filename>scala-library.jar</filename> in its class path. If using Scala IDE, you can copy it from somewhere under your Eclipse installation to the class path of the web application, that is, either to the <filename>WebContent/WEB-INF/lib</filename> folder in the project or to the library path of the application server. If copying outside Eclipse to a project, refresh the project by selecting it and pressing <keycap>F5</keycap>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1976
#, no-c-format
msgid "You could also get it with an Ivy or Maven dependency, just make sure that the version is same as what the Scala IDE uses."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1983
#, no-c-format
msgid "You should now be able to create a Scala UI class, such as the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: programlisting
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1987
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<?pocket-size 75% ?><![CDATA[@Theme(\"mytheme\")\n"
"class MyScalaUI extends UI {\n"
"  override def init(request: VaadinRequest) = {\n"
"    val content: VerticalLayout = new VerticalLayout\n"
"    setContent(content)\n"
"\n"
"    val label: Label = new Label(\"Hello, world!\")\n"
"    content addComponent label\n"
"\n"
"    // Handle user interaction\n"
"    content addComponent new Button(\"Click Me!\",\n"
"      new ClickListener {\n"
"        override def buttonClick(event: ClickEvent) =\n"
"          Notification.show(\"The time is \" + new Date)\n"
"      })\n"
"  }\n"
"}]]>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1989
#, no-c-format
msgid "Eclipse and Scala IDE should be able to import the Vaadin classes automatically when you press <keycombo><keycap>Ctrl</keycap><keycap>Shift</keycap><keycap>O</keycap></keycombo>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: chapter-getting-started.xml:1995
#, no-c-format
msgid "You need to define the Scala UI class either in a servlet class (in Servlet 3.0 project) or in a <filename>web.xml</filename> deployment descriptor, just like described in <xref linkend=\"getting-started.first-project.exploring\"/> for Java UIs."
msgstr ""

